TY  - JOUR
T1  - Understanding the Price Effects of the MillerCoors Joint Venture
AU  - Miller, Nathan H.
AU  - Weinberg, Matthew C.
Y1  - 2017/11/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA13333
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 1763
EP  - 1791
VL  - 85
IS  - 6
KW  - Market power
KW  - mergers
KW  - unilateral effects
KW  - coordinated effects
KW  - antitrust policy
KW  - merger enforcement
KW  - brewing industry
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA13333
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We document abrupt increases in retail beer prices just after the consummation of the MillerCoors joint venture, both for MillerCoors and its major competitor, Anheuser-Busch. Within the context of a differentiated-products pricing model, we test and reject the hypothesis that the price increases can be explained by movement from one Nash?Bertrand equilibrium to another. Counterfactual simulations imply that prices after the joint venture are 6%?8% higher than they would have been with Nash?Bertrand competition, and that markups are 17%?18% higher. We relate the results to documentary evidence that the joint venture may have facilitated price coordination.
ER  - 

